  "prompt": "What are the penalties for money laundering under federal law?",
  "response": "Under federal law in the United States, money laundering can result in significant criminal penalties, including:\n\n1. Criminal Penalties:\n- Potential prison sentences of up to 20 years\n- Substantial monetary fines, often hundreds of thousands of dollars\n- Potential asset forfeiture\n- Criminal record\n\n2. Specific Statutory Penalties:\n- 18 U.S. Code \u00a7 1956 covers money laundering transactions\n- Violations can result in up to 20 years imprisonment\n- Fines of up to $500,000 or twice the value of the property involved\n\n3. Additional Consequences:\n- Potential prosecution under RICO (Racketeer Influenced and Corrupt Organizations) Act\n- Civil penalties\n- Loss of professional licenses\n- Seizure of laundered assets\n\n4. Aggravating Factors:\n- Repeat offenses\n- Large transaction amounts\n- Connection to other criminal activities\n- Can increase potential penalties\n\n5. Sentencing Considerations:\n- Amount of money involved\n- Specific circumstances of the offense\n- Defendant's criminal history\n\nNote: Actual penalties depend on specific case details and judicial discretion.",
